To give a little more detail on the difference between type inference and dynamic typing, the following code is valid in a dynamic language, but a static language rejects it:<p><pre><code>    auto x = 15;
    if (some_condition) {
        x = &quot;Hello world!&quot;;
    }
    print(x);
</code></pre>
And this solves real errors. I believe there&#x27;s even a function somewhere in the Python <i>standard library</i> that, if it finds one result, returns a string, and if it finds multiple results, returns a list of strings. Of course a string is itself iterable, so duck-typing goes horribly wrong.
